			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">This isn't the end of viruses, but it is a promising theraputic route.  It doesn't cure these chronic infections, it hasn't been tried in humans, and it gives a whole new meaning to the phrase "skyrocketing medical costs".
<br />

<br />
Each dose of this stuff must be prepared from the patient's own blood, custom made.  That's gonna put the absolute bare-bones minimum cost for this stuff at something like $50,000 per treatment...maybe dropping to $35,000 if it can be done on an outpatient basis at a specialty clinic.
<br />

<br />
You need to draw the patient's blood, separate out the dendritic cells and the virus particles, then prepare the serum.  All working under the sort of biohazard containment any known hot HIV sample is going to require.
<br />

<br />
This is NOT gonna be something we can ever mass produce.  And as far as a preventative vaccine goes, it's not promising.  This doesn't get around the ability of HIV to mutate like crazy, spawning new strains.  This mostly looks like a way to treat the chronic infections like Hepatitis and AIDS.
<br />

<br />
Still, good news for Hepatitis and AIDS patients.  Just dont go all hog wild thinking the cure for the common cold is around the corner.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
