			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Relbeek...
<br />

<br />
Ugh.  I'm not trying to offend you...well, any more than is necessary to burst your bubble anyway...I'm trying to insert a little realism.
<br />

<br />
Anyone who's worked in Research and Development knows that NOTHING is more destructive to your long-term credibility than overstating the case on a new development or breakthrough.
<br />

<br />
Did you read the article and see how cautious the author was to couch everything in terms of "we saw this" or "work is ongoing"?  If you came up to him and said "Congrats, you've just discovered the cure to AIDS" he'd say "No, I didn't, the work is very interesting and shows promise but if I phrased it that way I'd sound like a total crackpot."
<br />

<br />
Correcting claims like that is something I caught as a spinal reflex during my years at 3M.  "Gee this material will let us corner the market and make billions" was automatically countered with "Well, the performance is promising, but we're still having issues scaling-up the synthesis, and we have definite work to do in perfecting the coating process..."
<br />

<br />
If somebody phrases it as "Here's the cure to AIDS" he's trying to scam you into buying stock in a nonexistant company.  That's the conventional wisdom.  And the reason such hyperbole causes instant teeth-grinding among product-development types is because it actually makes the necessary research LESS likely to be funded in the long run.
<br />

<br />
Read a Dilbert cartoon where Dilbert is watching Marketing types talk to a customer if you need a further illustration.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
