			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">As someone this concerns <img src="images/smiles/icon_wink.gif" alt="icon_wink.gif" border="0" />, I'd say protease inhibitors are still more promising.
<br />

<br />
They're developing one for Hep C now. (The problem with protease inhibitors is they have to be specifically engineered for each virus.)
<br />

<br />
The HIV protease inhibitor is the main reason HIV patients have 30-60 years or more instead of a death sentence now.
<br />

<br />
As for simply reducing viral loads, Ribavirin already does a pretty good job. The problem is, quality of life on Ribavirin bites ass (sides can include both homicidal and suicidal ideation, let alone total loss of libido), so they don't want to keep you on it for too long, and once you stop taking it the virus builds up again. (I came close to a hundredfold drop in my viral count last course of Ribavirin and Interferon, hoping for going completely clear this time. But my virus load was back over 1,000,000/uL between treatments.)
<br />

<br />
The real plan, though, is to live the five years it's going to take for them to finish testing and get them damn protease inhibitors on the market.<br />_________________<br />Bangzoom
<br />
68th Ranger of Doomnation
<br />
Veteran Crew Through and Through
<br />
